00:00:24.638 --> 00:00:26.680 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Well,
welcome to "Beyond Belief".

00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:31.060 align:middle line:10%
Dr. Bruce Damer is a scientist,
designer, intellectual working

00:00:31.060 --> 00:00:34.150 align:middle line:10%
on the key question of
how life started on Earth,

00:00:34.150 --> 00:00:35.710 align:middle line:10%
the future of humanity.

00:00:35.710 --> 00:00:37.540 align:middle line:84%
As we expand in
this space, you're

00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:40.000 align:middle line:84%
going to enjoy our
"Beyond Belief" program.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:41.510 align:middle line:90%
Bruce, welcome to the program.

00:00:41.510 --> 00:00:42.130 align:middle line:84%
>>BRUCE DAMER:
Thank you, George.

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:43.505 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How did
you get involved

00:00:43.505 --> 00:00:46.270 align:middle line:84%
in all of this, investigating
life out there and life here?

00:00:46.270 --> 00:00:47.770 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: You know,
when I was a kid,

00:00:47.770 --> 00:00:50.260 align:middle line:84%
I watched Neil Armstrong
step down onto the moon,

00:00:50.260 --> 00:00:52.180 align:middle line:90%
and I was hooked on live TV.

00:00:52.180 --> 00:00:53.380 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How old were you?

00:00:53.380 --> 00:00:54.380 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: I was seven.

00:00:54.380 --> 00:00:57.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I was 13, and
it was fascinating.

00:00:57.770 --> 00:00:59.650 align:middle line:90%
And I, too, watched that.

00:00:59.650 --> 00:01:01.240 align:middle line:90%
And it was unbelievable.

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:03.760 align:middle line:84%
Grainy black and white,
but it worked, didn't it?

00:01:03.760 --> 00:01:04.660 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: It worked.

00:01:04.660 --> 00:01:06.970 align:middle line:10%
And then when I
was 14, I decided

00:01:06.970 --> 00:01:10.570 align:middle line:10%
the coolest question to work
on for a nerdy kid like me was

00:01:10.570 --> 00:01:13.930 align:middle line:10%
how did life begin from
a jumble of molecules?

00:01:13.930 --> 00:01:15.740 align:middle line:84%
So I had my first
thought experiment.

00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:18.850 align:middle line:84%
You know how Albert Einstein
had thought experiments?

00:01:18.850 --> 00:01:22.480 align:middle line:84%
And it was a jumble of
molecules self-assembling kind

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:25.530 align:middle line:84%
of in my third eye,
in my imagination.

00:01:25.530 --> 00:01:29.260 align:middle line:84%
And I could speak to it, and I
asked it, how did life begin?

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:33.400 align:middle line:84%
And it said, figure out how
I made a copy of myself.

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:35.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now did you get
spiritual or religious at all

00:01:35.650 --> 00:01:36.760 align:middle line:90%
during this period?

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:37.930 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: I kind of was.

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:40.800 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know what
spiritual or religious was.

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:43.360 align:middle line:10%
But I always felt there
was this etheric feel

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:45.320 align:middle line:10%
that I was in contact with.

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:46.810 align:middle line:84%
And it also contained
these thought

00:01:46.810 --> 00:01:49.730 align:middle line:84%
experiments that contained
visions of the future.

00:01:49.730 --> 00:01:50.732 align:middle line:90%
So as a little kid--

00:01:50.732 --> 00:01:52.565 align:middle line:84%
I mean, all little kids
are pretty etherial.

00:01:52.565 --> 00:01:53.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:01:53.590 --> 00:01:54.965 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Pretty dreamy, yeah.

00:01:54.965 --> 00:01:56.590 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So you're
going to mix science

00:01:56.590 --> 00:02:01.150 align:middle line:84%
with spirituality to get us
this answer on how life began?

00:02:01.150 --> 00:02:02.870 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: In a
sense, I have, yeah.

00:02:02.870 --> 00:02:03.670 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:02:03.670 --> 00:02:06.970 align:middle line:84%
So if you study Newton,
if you study Descartes,

00:02:06.970 --> 00:02:10.240 align:middle line:84%
they use dreams to
do their science.

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:11.860 align:middle line:84%
So it's a long
tradition in science.

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:13.693 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What do you
think of Charles Darwin

00:02:13.693 --> 00:02:14.890 align:middle line:90%
and his theory of evolution?

00:02:14.890 --> 00:02:15.610 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Very powerful.

00:02:15.610 --> 00:02:16.000 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Really?

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:17.958 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Very powerful,
but not quite complete.

00:02:17.958 --> 00:02:20.445 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because there's a
camp that doesn't accept him.

00:02:20.445 --> 00:02:21.820 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Well,
what we've done is

00:02:21.820 --> 00:02:25.210 align:middle line:84%
we've extended it because
there's missing pieces to it.

00:02:25.210 --> 00:02:27.290 align:middle line:84%
And with this origin
of life model,

00:02:27.290 --> 00:02:30.430 align:middle line:84%
we've made the
discovery that we came

00:02:30.430 --> 00:02:33.220 align:middle line:84%
not from, probably,
competing individuals,

00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:35.580 align:middle line:84%
you know, fighting
red in tooth and claw,

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:37.120 align:middle line:84%
but from a
collaborative community

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:40.510 align:middle line:84%
complex, that the origin,
our common ancestor

00:02:40.510 --> 00:02:42.343 align:middle line:90%
is a complex community.

00:02:42.343 --> 00:02:44.260 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But don't you
think, Bruce, somewhere

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:46.850 align:middle line:84%
along the line, there's some
kind of intelligent planning

00:02:46.850 --> 00:02:47.650 align:middle line:90%
here?

00:02:47.650 --> 00:02:48.880 align:middle line:90%
This can't be an accident.

00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:50.080 align:middle line:90%
It can't be random.

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:51.460 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: You would think so.

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:56.080 align:middle line:84%
But if you look in complexity
theory, when networks form,

00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:59.500 align:middle line:84%
they grow faster than
the individuals can.

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:02.660 align:middle line:84%
So in sense that etheric
field that I contacted

00:03:02.660 --> 00:03:04.660 align:middle line:84%
when I was a kid, and I
didn't know what it was,

00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:09.100 align:middle line:84%
could possibly be explained
by complex weaving of life

00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:10.237 align:middle line:90%
that we can't even see.

00:03:10.237 --> 00:03:11.320 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Interesting take.

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:14.410 align:middle line:84%
My thoughts on all of
this is because I'm

00:03:14.410 --> 00:03:17.590 align:middle line:84%
such a strong believer
in intelligent design,

00:03:17.590 --> 00:03:20.750 align:middle line:84%
is that we all have
to live with water.

00:03:20.750 --> 00:03:21.550 align:middle line:90%
We have to.

00:03:21.550 --> 00:03:23.260 align:middle line:90%
Without that, we're gone.

00:03:23.260 --> 00:03:24.460 align:middle line:90%
Everything's gone.

00:03:24.460 --> 00:03:29.110 align:middle line:84%
Trees are gone, grass is gone,
we're gone, everything's gone.

00:03:29.110 --> 00:03:31.630 align:middle line:84%
Who would conceive
of the plan to make

00:03:31.630 --> 00:03:37.630 align:middle line:84%
it rain on plants and trees
when you need the water there?

00:03:37.630 --> 00:03:39.730 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that alone
tells me there's

00:03:39.730 --> 00:03:41.800 align:middle line:90%
some kind of planning to this.

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:44.050 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: It's a hard
one to figure out.

00:03:44.050 --> 00:03:46.840 align:middle line:84%
But when we go to
Mars, the rain stopped

00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:49.170 align:middle line:90%
about four billion years ago.

00:03:49.170 --> 00:03:50.650 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And so did the life.

00:03:50.650 --> 00:03:52.420 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: If it ever
got started there.

00:03:52.420 --> 00:03:54.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, we
think it did, don't we?

00:03:54.790 --> 00:03:57.040 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Well, there's
a whiff of methane

00:03:57.040 --> 00:03:59.200 align:middle line:84%
that seems to be coming
up through the rocks.

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:00.820 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So what
does that tell you?

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:02.800 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: There could
be methane-eating or

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:04.622 align:middle line:84%
methane-producing
life in the rocks.

00:04:04.622 --> 00:04:06.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Or in the little
organisms down there,

00:04:06.580 --> 00:04:08.050 align:middle line:90%
or critters.

00:04:08.050 --> 00:04:10.600 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Probably bacteria,
kind of like the plaque

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:11.930 align:middle line:90%
on your teeth.

00:04:11.930 --> 00:04:13.430 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But to me,
that's not life.

00:04:13.430 --> 00:04:16.649 align:middle line:84%
I want to see an
animal or something.

00:04:16.649 --> 00:04:17.540 align:middle line:90%
That's life to me.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:19.540 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Yeah, you want
something driving around

00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:21.200 align:middle line:90%
in something.

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:23.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Back to the
Charles Darwin theory.

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:25.100 align:middle line:90%
What does he say?

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:28.280 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: So he says
that the only mechanism

00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:32.150 align:middle line:84%
you need to generate complex
forms from earlier ones

00:04:32.150 --> 00:04:35.070 align:middle line:84%
is a process of
natural selection.

00:04:35.070 --> 00:04:36.740 align:middle line:90%
We have a big population.

00:04:36.740 --> 00:04:40.550 align:middle line:84%
One of them gets through
and spreads its genes,

00:04:40.550 --> 00:04:42.870 align:middle line:84%
and then you have
another set of selection,

00:04:42.870 --> 00:04:45.320 align:middle line:84%
and then another
population, and then

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:47.210 align:middle line:90%
the strongest one gets through.

00:04:47.210 --> 00:04:50.570 align:middle line:84%
And it's a staircasing
thing, kind of like economics

00:04:50.570 --> 00:04:51.670 align:middle line:90%
with companies competing.

00:04:51.670 --> 00:04:54.170 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Bruce, you had a chance
to go to New Zealand, where

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:55.920 align:middle line:90%
you did some incredible things.

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:58.006 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look.

00:04:58.006 --> 00:04:59.860 align:middle line:90%
