00:05:30.810 --> 00:05:33.420 align:middle line:10%
a collaborative community
was at the taproot

00:05:33.420 --> 00:05:35.130 align:middle line:10%
of the tree of life.

00:05:35.130 --> 00:05:38.100 align:middle line:84%
- Dr. Damer's research
could turn previous origins

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:40.200 align:middle line:90%
of life science on its hit.

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:42.540 align:middle line:84%
His testing with a
hot springs on land

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:46.080 align:middle line:84%
may have been the starting
point for life itself.

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:49.800 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Damer's searching
for RNA, a nucleic acid

00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:52.630 align:middle line:90%
and the basis of living cells.

00:05:52.630 --> 00:05:55.200 align:middle line:10%
- So what we think
is that RNA could

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:58.920 align:middle line:10%
have been the first polymer
that life synthesized first

00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:00.930 align:middle line:10%
at random in a
process like this,

00:06:00.930 --> 00:06:03.450 align:middle line:10%
and then picked
through selection

00:06:03.450 --> 00:06:05.670 align:middle line:10%
through these
cycling protocells,

00:06:05.670 --> 00:06:07.950 align:middle line:10%
which we're doing here
in the hot spring,

00:06:07.950 --> 00:06:09.720 align:middle line:10%
picked ones that worked.

00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:11.970 align:middle line:10%
- He's also hoping
to conduct research

00:06:11.970 --> 00:06:14.160 align:middle line:10%
into the formation of
a molecular structure

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:16.130 align:middle line:10%
much closer to home.

00:06:16.130 --> 00:06:19.830 align:middle line:10%
- It's possible, also,
that DNA could have formed

00:06:19.830 --> 00:06:22.680 align:middle line:10%
in a condition like
this, self-assembled.

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:25.260 align:middle line:10%
So those little double
helical polymers

00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:28.360 align:middle line:10%
self-assembling just like
we're doing with the RNA here,

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:31.650 align:middle line:10%
and that DNA may have been
around the same time as RNA,

00:06:31.650 --> 00:06:33.240 align:middle line:10%
and then they could interact.

00:06:33.240 --> 00:06:36.870 align:middle line:10%
And the DNA acts as a
data store for the RNA,

00:06:36.870 --> 00:06:38.970 align:middle line:10%
which reads the data
store and then makes all

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:41.790 align:middle line:10%
the proteins that make life.

00:06:41.790 --> 00:06:44.340 align:middle line:84%
- For years scientists
had accepted the theory

00:06:44.340 --> 00:06:47.730 align:middle line:84%
that life began in hydrothermal
vents in the ocean.

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:51.240 align:middle line:10%
Charles Darwin once speculated
that biological molecules might

00:06:51.240 --> 00:06:54.180 align:middle line:10%
form in a warm little
pond, and Doctor Damer

00:06:54.180 --> 00:06:57.060 align:middle line:10%
believes this to be much
closer to the truth.

00:06:57.060 --> 00:07:00.540 align:middle line:10%
- If we can show to our
colleagues and to the world

00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:04.140 align:middle line:10%
that we can self-assemble an
important biopolymer of life

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:08.533 align:middle line:10%
called RNA in a hot spring
pool that's cycling,

00:07:08.533 --> 00:07:10.950 align:middle line:10%
in the conditions that would
have been around in the early

00:07:10.950 --> 00:07:13.110 align:middle line:10%
Earth on these big
volcanic islands,

00:07:13.110 --> 00:07:16.110 align:middle line:10%
our colleagues are really going
to seriously look at doing more

00:07:16.110 --> 00:07:17.130 align:middle line:10%
experiments.

00:07:17.130 --> 00:07:19.230 align:middle line:84%
And it'll create a whole
movement, a whole sort

00:07:19.230 --> 00:07:22.230 align:middle line:84%
of paradigm shift in origin
of life thinking back

00:07:22.230 --> 00:07:24.720 align:middle line:84%
to Darwin's warm
little pond, only now

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:26.390 align:middle line:90%
it's a cycling hot little pool.

00:07:26.390 --> 00:07:27.190 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:07:27.190 --> 00:07:28.350 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Bruce,
did you find what

00:07:28.350 --> 00:07:29.610 align:middle line:90%
you were looking for there?

00:07:29.610 --> 00:07:30.930 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: We did.

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:34.500 align:middle line:84%
What we did was put the
building blocks of RNA

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:37.070 align:middle line:84%
in those solutions,
in those little vials,

00:07:37.070 --> 00:07:41.160 align:middle line:84%
dried them down, and rehydrated
them with hot spring water.

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:42.990 align:middle line:84%
They formed films,
and then they formed

00:07:42.990 --> 00:07:45.530 align:middle line:90%
protocells that contained RNA.

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:48.540 align:middle line:84%
And as this was happening, they
stitched the building blocks

00:07:48.540 --> 00:07:53.190 align:middle line:84%
together into RNA long enough
to do functions, to do biology.

00:07:53.190 --> 00:07:57.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why was the hot springs
water so important to this?

00:07:57.420 --> 00:07:58.920 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: It was a
perfect marriage

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:02.670 align:middle line:84%
of just the right protons,
basically, in the acidic water,

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:04.860 align:middle line:84%
and the drying down, the
right heat, and the right

00:08:04.860 --> 00:08:09.810 align:middle line:84%
drawing down to do the chemistry
that then life took over later.

00:08:09.810 --> 00:08:12.220 align:middle line:84%
So we have a chicken
and egg problem

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:15.920 align:middle line:84%
in that you need to form
polymers to have living things.

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:18.030 align:middle line:84%
But you can't do
it without enzymes,

00:08:18.030 --> 00:08:21.150 align:middle line:84%
and we found that nature
had this technique,

00:08:21.150 --> 00:08:25.110 align:middle line:84%
wet dry cycling, to be able to
do that job without enzymes.

00:08:25.110 --> 00:08:28.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Without this, would
there been life on Earth?

00:08:28.410 --> 00:08:29.430 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Probably not.

00:08:29.430 --> 00:08:30.230 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Really?

00:08:30.230 --> 00:08:31.140 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Yeah.

00:08:31.140 --> 00:08:34.860 align:middle line:84%
So wet dry cycling, so you
need volcanic landscapes

00:08:34.860 --> 00:08:37.320 align:middle line:84%
with things like Old
Faithful that are constantly

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:39.360 align:middle line:90%
filling and refilling pools.

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:42.480 align:middle line:84%
And we've done this in the
lab for 10 years, George.

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:45.240 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now what about other
planets out there like Mars?

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:48.160 align:middle line:10%
Do they have that kind
of system going on, too?

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:48.960 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Yes.

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:53.060 align:middle line:84%
Mars-- the Spirit Rover,
which went to Mars

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:55.050 align:middle line:84%
and traveled for
about seven years,

00:08:55.050 --> 00:08:57.510 align:middle line:84%
found an old hot spring
in Old Yellowstone

00:08:57.510 --> 00:08:59.100 align:middle line:90%
3.7 billion years old.

00:08:59.100 --> 00:08:59.900 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:00.700 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Yeah.

00:09:00.700 --> 00:09:04.650 align:middle line:84%
And what we're looking for on
Mars is something like this.

00:09:04.650 --> 00:09:05.610 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What is that?

00:09:05.610 --> 00:09:07.532 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: That's a
stromatolite from Australia.

00:09:07.532 --> 00:09:08.490 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: May I feel it?

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:09.690 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Yeah.

00:09:09.690 --> 00:09:11.550 align:middle line:84%
It's got these
little ripples in it.

00:09:11.550 --> 00:09:13.290 align:middle line:90%
You can see the ripples in it.

00:09:13.290 --> 00:09:15.390 align:middle line:90%
That's the biofilms.

00:09:15.390 --> 00:09:16.330 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's heavy.

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:18.122 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: It's heavy,
and it's full of iron.

00:09:18.122 --> 00:09:20.220 align:middle line:84%
So the early Earth
was red, like Mars.

00:09:20.220 --> 00:09:21.720 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: This is
what you don't want

00:09:21.720 --> 00:09:24.690 align:middle line:84%
to hit the planet,
because if it's iron,

00:09:24.690 --> 00:09:26.040 align:middle line:90%
it doesn't break down, does it?

00:09:26.040 --> 00:09:26.957 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: That's right.

00:09:26.957 --> 00:09:27.870 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:30.250 align:middle line:90%
And so that's from Australia.

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:34.020 align:middle line:84%
And that's some of the oldest
evidence of life on Earth.

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:38.010 align:middle line:84%
So of the Mars 2020
Rover found such a thing

00:09:38.010 --> 00:09:42.840 align:middle line:84%
at the surface in 2021, we'd
have reasonable evidence

00:09:42.840 --> 00:09:45.240 align:middle line:84%
that life was on
the surface of Mars.

00:09:45.240 --> 00:09:47.620 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Life would be
all over this thing?

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:50.470 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Well, what that is
is the fingerprint of life.

00:09:50.470 --> 00:09:52.800 align:middle line:90%
So this is an old lake shore.

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:54.690 align:middle line:84%
And when you go to
lake shores and you

00:09:54.690 --> 00:09:58.350 align:middle line:84%
see that slimy stuff that's
really stinky in kind

00:09:58.350 --> 00:10:03.000 align:middle line:84%
of mudflats, that's producing
oxygen, it's producing sulfur.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.970 align:middle line:84%
But when sediments
wash over it, they

00:10:05.970 --> 00:10:08.580 align:middle line:84%
cement the sediments
together and make a platform,

00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:10.080 align:middle line:84%
and that's what
these layers are.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:14.400 align:middle line:84%
So it's the fingerprint of
life three billion years ago.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:16.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And that could be
on how many other planetary

00:10:16.650 --> 00:10:18.952 align:middle line:84%
systems, let's say,
in our solar system?

00:10:18.952 --> 00:10:20.160 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: It could be on Mars.

00:10:20.160 --> 00:10:24.310 align:middle line:84%
It could have been on Venus, but
Venus, the oceans boiled off.

00:10:24.310 --> 00:10:25.110 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Too hot.

00:10:25.110 --> 00:10:26.130 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Too hot.

00:10:26.130 --> 00:10:29.430 align:middle line:84%
The moons of Saturn,
with their icy shells,

00:10:29.430 --> 00:10:32.610 align:middle line:84%
maybe life couldn't start
there because for this model,

00:10:32.610 --> 00:10:33.750 align:middle line:90%
you need wet dry cycling.

00:10:33.750 --> 00:10:35.370 align:middle line:90%
You need landscape.

00:10:35.370 --> 00:10:37.473 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What about
Europa, Jupiter's moon?

00:10:37.473 --> 00:10:38.890 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Yeah,
it's covered in ice

00:10:38.890 --> 00:10:42.430 align:middle line:84%
and there's a deep ocean, which
might have hydrothermal systems

00:10:42.430 --> 00:10:43.230 align:middle line:90%
like a hot spring.

00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:45.150 align:middle line:84%
But because you have
water, you can't

00:10:45.150 --> 00:10:48.510 align:middle line:84%
form the chemicals of life
without them breaking down

00:10:48.510 --> 00:10:49.585 align:middle line:90%
first.

00:10:49.585 --> 00:10:50.460 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Interesting.

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:54.328 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: And Titan, which has
basically a hydrocarbon sea--

00:10:54.328 --> 00:10:55.620 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Moon of Saturn, right?

00:10:55.620 --> 00:10:56.670 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Moon of Saturn.

00:10:56.670 --> 00:10:58.500 align:middle line:90%
Titan's maybe too cold.

00:10:58.500 --> 00:10:59.880 align:middle line:90%
But missions are going to Titan.

00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:01.380 align:middle line:84%
The dragonfly mission
will go there.

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:03.960 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, we call our
system the Goldilocks spot,

00:11:03.960 --> 00:11:06.750 align:middle line:84%
right, because it's got
just the right temperature,

00:11:06.750 --> 00:11:08.490 align:middle line:90%
the right ingredients.

00:11:08.490 --> 00:11:11.520 align:middle line:84%
But with billions of
planets in the universe,

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:15.180 align:middle line:84%
billions of planets,
the percent of planets

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:18.727 align:middle line:84%
that would be similar to ours
is astronomical, isn't it?

00:11:18.727 --> 00:11:20.310 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: There would
be a lot of them.

00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:26.070 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, if they
can form these microbial mats,

00:11:26.070 --> 00:11:28.820 align:middle line:84%
maybe that's common because
if you have wet dry cycling,

00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:32.580 align:middle line:84%
you have volcanic landscapes,
a lot of water that's present.

00:11:32.580 --> 00:11:34.110 align:middle line:90%
But here's the trick.

00:11:34.110 --> 00:11:37.920 align:middle line:84%
You need to have those microbial
mats able to grow and flourish

00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:40.683 align:middle line:84%
for three or four billion
years to produce oxygen.

00:11:40.683 --> 00:11:41.850 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It takes that long?

00:11:41.850 --> 00:11:43.620 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: It takes that long.

00:11:43.620 --> 00:11:46.500 align:middle line:84%
So the oxygen and then
transition to bigger cells

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:50.220 align:middle line:84%
called eukaryotes, which
then form the first worms,

00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:53.280 align:middle line:90%
the first fungi, first plants.

00:11:53.280 --> 00:11:56.190 align:middle line:84%
And then the oxygen
feeds their metabolisms,

00:11:56.190 --> 00:11:58.140 align:middle line:90%
gives them the energy they need.

00:11:58.140 --> 00:12:01.453 align:middle line:90%
And then we get to big animals.

00:12:01.453 --> 00:12:03.120 align:middle line:84%
And then you have to
have the right path

00:12:03.120 --> 00:12:06.660 align:middle line:84%
to the right big animals and
the right mass extinctions

00:12:06.660 --> 00:12:09.660 align:middle line:90%
to get to thinking animals.

00:12:09.660 --> 00:12:13.320 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The possibilities of
life originating like we have

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:16.590 align:middle line:84%
here on planet Earth, where
we're at the top of the totem

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:18.390 align:middle line:90%
pole--

00:12:18.390 --> 00:12:21.130 align:middle line:84%
what are the odds of
that on other planets?

00:12:21.130 --> 00:12:23.340 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: There's a great
book called "Rare Earth"

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:25.230 align:middle line:90%
that really spells it all out.

00:12:25.230 --> 00:12:28.590 align:middle line:84%
I think the odds are
likely because there's

00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:31.620 align:middle line:84%
so many of those
planets, but still small,

00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:33.780 align:middle line:84%
because the pathway
that you have

00:12:33.780 --> 00:12:36.990 align:middle line:84%
to get through to get
to big thinking animals

00:12:36.990 --> 00:12:38.850 align:middle line:90%
is so unlikely.

00:12:38.850 --> 00:12:42.660 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You've worked for
NASA 20 years at least, right?

00:12:42.660 --> 00:12:46.480 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things you
focus on are asteroid missions.

00:12:46.480 --> 00:12:47.952 align:middle line:90%
Let's look.

00:12:47.952 --> 00:12:49.365 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:49.365 --> 00:12:52.670 align:middle line:90%


00:12:52.670 --> 00:12:55.890 align:middle line:10%
- The Near Earth Object,
NEOs, as they're called,

00:12:55.890 --> 00:12:57.490 align:middle line:10%
turn out to be
some of the easiest

00:12:57.490 --> 00:12:59.380 align:middle line:10%
places in the solar
system to reach

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:01.616 align:middle line:10%
in terms of the propulsion
energy required.

00:13:01.616 --> 00:13:03.600 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:08.570 align:middle line:90%


00:13:08.570 --> 00:13:11.060 align:middle line:10%
This video describes a
hypothetical human mission

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:13.670 align:middle line:10%
to an asteroid that might
pass nearby the Earth sometime

00:13:13.670 --> 00:13:16.340 align:middle line:10%
in the 21st century.

00:13:16.340 --> 00:13:18.920 align:middle line:10%
NASA asked Digital Space,
a California company

00:13:18.920 --> 00:13:20.870 align:middle line:10%
that has worked with
NASA for many years,

00:13:20.870 --> 00:13:23.570 align:middle line:10%
to create this designed to
show how NASA's next generation

00:13:23.570 --> 00:13:26.510 align:middle line:10%
constellation program for
returning humans to the moon

00:13:26.510 --> 00:13:30.280 align:middle line:10%
could also take on a so-called
deep space mission like this.

00:13:30.280 --> 00:13:33.050 align:middle line:10%
Two constellation
launches are required.

00:13:33.050 --> 00:13:35.570 align:middle line:10%
The first is an
uncrewed Aires 5 launch

00:13:35.570 --> 00:13:40.010 align:middle line:10%
of a booster segment called the
Earth Departure Stage or EDS,

00:13:40.010 --> 00:13:42.440 align:middle line:10%
followed about 90 minutes
later by an Aires 1

00:13:42.440 --> 00:13:44.480 align:middle line:10%
lift of an Orion
crew exploration

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:47.330 align:middle line:10%
vehicle with astronauts aboard.

00:13:47.330 --> 00:13:52.850 align:middle line:10%
Mounted atop the EDS is the NEO
Surface Access Module or NSAM.

00:13:52.850 --> 00:13:55.310 align:middle line:84%
Astronauts in the
Orion rendezvous

00:13:55.310 --> 00:13:57.740 align:middle line:84%
and then dock with
the EDS and NSAM,

00:13:57.740 --> 00:14:00.890 align:middle line:84%
creating a complete
stack, as it's called.

00:14:00.890 --> 00:14:02.900 align:middle line:10%
When the appropriate
launch window arrives,

00:14:02.900 --> 00:14:07.250 align:middle line:10%
the powerful EDS engines fire,
injecting the entire stack

00:14:07.250 --> 00:14:11.800 align:middle line:10%
into a trajectory bound
for the target asteroid.

00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:16.000 align:middle line:10%
Approaching the NEO, the Orion
and NSAM separate from the EDS

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.945 align:middle line:10%
and take up a station-keeping
position nearby the NEO.

00:14:18.945 --> 00:14:22.330 align:middle line:10%
The mated vehicles now
match the NEO's rotation

00:14:22.330 --> 00:14:25.810 align:middle line:10%
and begin a descent towards
the asteroid surface.

00:14:25.810 --> 00:14:28.000 align:middle line:10%
Astronauts now rotate
their joined vehicles

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.220 align:middle line:10%
to an NSAM down
orientation so that they

00:14:31.220 --> 00:14:35.720 align:middle line:10%
can scan the NEO for a promising
place to moor their ship.

00:14:35.720 --> 00:14:37.220 align:middle line:84%
Up until this point,
the mission has

00:14:37.220 --> 00:14:40.180 align:middle line:84%
been very similar to an
Apollo approach to the moon,

00:14:40.180 --> 00:14:44.000 align:middle line:84%
but now some key
differences emerge.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.010 align:middle line:10%
Look carefully at the
bottom of the NSAM,

00:14:46.010 --> 00:14:48.380 align:middle line:10%
and you'll notice
a ring of airbags.

00:14:48.380 --> 00:14:50.180 align:middle line:10%
These have sensors
on their surfaces

00:14:50.180 --> 00:14:54.425 align:middle line:10%
and penetrometer
probes between them.

00:14:54.425 --> 00:14:56.050 align:middle line:10%
Mission planners are
designing for what

00:14:56.050 --> 00:14:59.380 align:middle line:10%
they call a soft contact and
tether on the NEO surface.

00:14:59.380 --> 00:15:02.990 align:middle line:90%


00:15:02.990 --> 00:15:05.630 align:middle line:10%
Because NEOs are much less
massive than the moon,

00:15:05.630 --> 00:15:07.070 align:middle line:10%
only a small amount
of thrust will

00:15:07.070 --> 00:15:11.340 align:middle line:10%
be required to balance the NEO's
tiny gravitational attraction.

00:15:11.340 --> 00:15:13.220 align:middle line:10%
So mission designers
don't refer to this

00:15:13.220 --> 00:15:18.240 align:middle line:10%
as a landing on the NEO surface,
but rather a docking with it.

00:15:18.240 --> 00:15:21.080 align:middle line:10%
It's more like one very
small spacecraft meeting up

00:15:21.080 --> 00:15:23.600 align:middle line:10%
with a very large one.

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:26.150 align:middle line:10%
When the stack first makes
contact with the surface,

00:15:26.150 --> 00:15:28.850 align:middle line:10%
software looks at the airbag
sensors and penetrometer

00:15:28.850 --> 00:15:31.370 align:middle line:10%
readings, decides quickly
if it's solid enough

00:15:31.370 --> 00:15:35.330 align:middle line:10%
to stay, or to back off and
try a different docking site.

00:15:35.330 --> 00:15:38.180 align:middle line:10%
If the vote is to remain,
harpoon-tipped tethers

00:15:38.180 --> 00:15:40.250 align:middle line:10%
fire into the nearby
surface in a bid

00:15:40.250 --> 00:15:43.370 align:middle line:10%
to keep the NSAM
anchored and upright.

00:15:43.370 --> 00:15:46.430 align:middle line:10%
The first small steps
for humans onto a NEO

00:15:46.430 --> 00:15:49.520 align:middle line:10%
had better be small Indeed,
as the ultra low gravity will

00:15:49.520 --> 00:15:52.100 align:middle line:10%
create conditions more
akin to scuba diving

00:15:52.100 --> 00:15:53.720 align:middle line:10%
than to moon walking.

00:15:53.720 --> 00:15:57.380 align:middle line:10%
NEOnauts, venturing out on
extravehicular activities,

00:15:57.380 --> 00:15:59.210 align:middle line:10%
as spacewalks are
called, will probably

00:15:59.210 --> 00:16:03.630 align:middle line:10%
need to keep a hand or foot
on their vehicle at all times.

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:06.050 align:middle line:10%
Fortunately, the
securely anchored tethers

00:16:06.050 --> 00:16:08.360 align:middle line:10%
will perform double
duty as handholds,

00:16:08.360 --> 00:16:10.130 align:middle line:10%
allowing astronauts
to make their way down

00:16:10.130 --> 00:16:13.220 align:middle line:10%
to and around the surface.

00:16:13.220 --> 00:16:16.820 align:middle line:10%
NEOs are likely to be very
crumbly and dirty places.

00:16:16.820 --> 00:16:19.280 align:middle line:10%
Any dust the astronauts
stir up will likely

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:21.170 align:middle line:10%
float around them and
cling to their suits

00:16:21.170 --> 00:16:23.740 align:middle line:10%
due to static electricity.

00:16:23.740 --> 00:16:27.040 align:middle line:10%
Working on an asteroid won't
be like last century's lunar

00:16:27.040 --> 00:16:29.320 align:middle line:10%
excursions.

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:31.450 align:middle line:84%
At first, NEOnaut
crews will only

00:16:31.450 --> 00:16:34.630 align:middle line:84%
explore very close
to their spacecraft.

00:16:34.630 --> 00:16:38.350 align:middle line:10%
But they could climb back inside
and hop the entire vehicle

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:40.270 align:middle line:10%
to other locations
on the asteroid

00:16:40.270 --> 00:16:42.340 align:middle line:10%
and take additional samples.

00:16:42.340 --> 00:16:45.250 align:middle line:10%
Eventually the NEOnauts
may use jet packs,

00:16:45.250 --> 00:16:47.380 align:middle line:10%
quite similar to the manned
maneuvering unit used

00:16:47.380 --> 00:16:50.440 align:middle line:10%
on the shuttle to freely
fly, perhaps quite far

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:52.030 align:middle line:10%
from the safety of the NSAM.

00:16:52.030 --> 00:16:55.630 align:middle line:10%
A lot of asteroid might be
covered in a single mission.

00:16:55.630 --> 00:16:57.460 align:middle line:10%
But when it's time
to go for good,

00:16:57.460 --> 00:17:00.220 align:middle line:10%
the Orion and NSAM
upper stage will

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:03.250 align:middle line:10%
unhook from the
tether decking segment

00:17:03.250 --> 00:17:06.450 align:middle line:10%
and pull away for
the return home.

00:17:06.450 --> 00:17:08.970 align:middle line:10%
Firmly affixed to the
NEO, the piece left behind

00:17:08.970 --> 00:17:12.750 align:middle line:10%
will become a long-term
robotic science station.

00:17:12.750 --> 00:17:15.599 align:middle line:10%
Back in free space and
NEOnauts no longer,

00:17:15.599 --> 00:17:18.369 align:middle line:10%
the group will perform a
direct entry flight profile

00:17:18.369 --> 00:17:22.770 align:middle line:10%
after dropping their NSAM living
quarters and Orion service

00:17:22.770 --> 00:17:25.319 align:middle line:10%
module along the way.

00:17:25.319 --> 00:17:27.300 align:middle line:10%
Like other Orion
missions, the crew

00:17:27.300 --> 00:17:33.780 align:middle line:10%
will experience a fiery
reentry, a parachute descent,

00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:36.510 align:middle line:10%
and then, most likely,
a splashdown-style water

00:17:36.510 --> 00:17:39.920 align:middle line:10%
landing and recovery.

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:42.710 align:middle line:10%
NEOs, it turns out, are
individuals, each different

00:17:42.710 --> 00:17:43.640 align:middle line:10%
from the other.

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:45.290 align:middle line:10%
Following this
basic mission plan,

00:17:45.290 --> 00:17:47.900 align:middle line:10%
additional sorties to
other NEOs could be flown.

00:17:47.900 --> 00:17:50.360 align:middle line:10%
Proponents of NEO missions
cite several reasons

00:17:50.360 --> 00:17:52.340 align:middle line:10%
for wanting to do
these missions.

00:17:52.340 --> 00:17:54.590 align:middle line:10%
They think that NEO
samples selected

00:17:54.590 --> 00:17:57.740 align:middle line:10%
by an intelligent human science
crew right there on the surface

00:17:57.740 --> 00:18:00.440 align:middle line:10%
will likely hold amazing
planetary geoscience

00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:02.210 align:middle line:10%
discoveries.

00:18:02.210 --> 00:18:04.800 align:middle line:10%
The impact threat from
NEOs is always present.

00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:07.010 align:middle line:10%
So it's probably a good
idea for our civilization

00:18:07.010 --> 00:18:09.170 align:middle line:10%
to learn as much
about them as we can.

00:18:09.170 --> 00:18:11.480 align:middle line:10%
In fact, one asteroid
named Apophis

00:18:11.480 --> 00:18:15.710 align:middle line:10%
will make a close encounter
with Earth in 2029.

00:18:15.710 --> 00:18:18.770 align:middle line:10%
But perhaps most important,
NEOs and icy objects

00:18:18.770 --> 00:18:21.200 align:middle line:10%
such as active comets
could be developed

00:18:21.200 --> 00:18:24.940 align:middle line:10%
as a rich resource
stepping stones

00:18:24.940 --> 00:18:28.730 align:middle line:10%
supporting future
human exploration

00:18:28.730 --> 00:18:32.950 align:middle line:10%
and the eventual permanent human
settlement of the solar system,

00:18:32.950 --> 00:18:36.589 align:middle line:10%
and maybe one day, beyond.

00:18:36.589 --> 00:18:40.040 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:18:40.040 --> 00:18:41.030 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:18:41.030 --> 00:18:45.160 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why, Bruce, would we
want to land on an asteroid?

00:18:45.160 --> 00:18:46.160 align:middle line:90%
What's there for us?

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:49.520 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: It turns out, George,
that these asteroids are

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:52.730 align:middle line:84%
made up of what we believe are
the building blocks of life

00:18:52.730 --> 00:18:55.040 align:middle line:90%
and what made us.

00:18:55.040 --> 00:18:57.285 align:middle line:84%
So if I take this,
and I take a smell--

00:18:57.285 --> 00:18:58.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What's that?

00:18:58.160 --> 00:19:00.440 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: This is
like cosmic dust.

00:19:00.440 --> 00:19:04.182 align:middle line:84%
It's a 4.6 billion-year-old
asteroid or meteorite.

00:19:04.182 --> 00:19:05.390 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Could barely see it.

00:19:05.390 --> 00:19:06.640 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Found on the Earth.

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:10.273 align:middle line:84%
And you smell it, you get
the smoky gunpowder smell.

00:19:10.273 --> 00:19:11.690 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: This is
from an asteroid?

00:19:11.690 --> 00:19:14.023 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: This is from an
asteroid that fell to the Earth

00:19:14.023 --> 00:19:15.090 align:middle line:90%
as a meteorite.

00:19:15.090 --> 00:19:16.340 align:middle line:90%
And it's older than the Earth.

00:19:16.340 --> 00:19:18.972 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How much is this worth?

00:19:18.972 --> 00:19:20.180 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Anyone name a price.

00:19:20.180 --> 00:19:21.570 align:middle line:90%
We'll put it on Craigslist.

00:19:21.570 --> 00:19:22.070 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Really?

00:19:22.070 --> 00:19:22.870 align:middle line:90%
Huh.

00:19:22.870 --> 00:19:25.790 align:middle line:90%


00:19:25.790 --> 00:19:30.050 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: So if we go to an
asteroid with a human crew,

00:19:30.050 --> 00:19:32.600 align:middle line:84%
we might be able to
find those organics that

00:19:32.600 --> 00:19:34.370 align:middle line:84%
are the clue to
how we were made,

00:19:34.370 --> 00:19:37.890 align:middle line:84%
all that organic material from
all those solar systems falling

00:19:37.890 --> 00:19:38.690 align:middle line:90%
into the Earth.

00:19:38.690 --> 00:19:41.600 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Isn't an
asteroid tumbling along?

00:19:41.600 --> 00:19:42.920 align:middle line:90%
How do you stay on it?

00:19:42.920 --> 00:19:44.212 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: How do you stay on it?

00:19:44.212 --> 00:19:46.430 align:middle line:84%
So in that mission, that's
a human-crewed mission

00:19:46.430 --> 00:19:48.830 align:middle line:84%
where you have to tether
down because there's almost

00:19:48.830 --> 00:19:49.840 align:middle line:90%
no gravity.

00:19:49.840 --> 00:19:51.740 align:middle line:90%
You go out on backpacks.

00:19:51.740 --> 00:19:53.000 align:middle line:90%
But what we also worked out--

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:54.950 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Can you get
flung off into space?

00:19:54.950 --> 00:19:56.740 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: It's pretty
slow rotation.

00:19:56.740 --> 00:19:57.540 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is.

00:19:57.540 --> 00:19:59.490 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: You could throw
a baseball, George,

00:19:59.490 --> 00:20:01.460 align:middle line:90%
and it wouldn't end up in orbit.

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:02.880 align:middle line:90%
One of those things.

00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:05.150 align:middle line:84%
But what we also
worked out is a method

00:20:05.150 --> 00:20:09.020 align:middle line:84%
by which to encapsulate an
asteroid in a balloon fabric

00:20:09.020 --> 00:20:12.870 align:middle line:84%
structure, like Bigelow's
building now, and fill it

00:20:12.870 --> 00:20:13.670 align:middle line:90%
with gas.

00:20:13.670 --> 00:20:15.380 align:middle line:90%
And we'll stop the rotation.

00:20:15.380 --> 00:20:17.940 align:middle line:84%
The tumbling will
stop in the friction.

00:20:17.940 --> 00:20:21.890 align:middle line:84%
Then we can use, like, a sailing
ship technology to push gas

00:20:21.890 --> 00:20:23.900 align:middle line:90%
at the asteroid and push it.

00:20:23.900 --> 00:20:26.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, you're talking
about maybe a 30-foot asteroid

00:20:26.510 --> 00:20:27.310 align:middle line:90%
or something.

00:20:27.310 --> 00:20:29.750 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: 30 foot up
to a half a mile.

00:20:29.750 --> 00:20:31.850 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: A half a mile
balloon-type thing

00:20:31.850 --> 00:20:32.120 align:middle line:90%
to encase it?

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:32.920 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Yeah.

00:20:32.920 --> 00:20:34.790 align:middle line:90%
We could scale up.

00:20:34.790 --> 00:20:37.580 align:middle line:84%
And why we would do this
is to extract materials

00:20:37.580 --> 00:20:41.330 align:middle line:84%
like this and water ice to
create fuel stations for Elon

00:20:41.330 --> 00:20:44.092 align:middle line:84%
Musk's Mars mission, for
example, because Elon needs--

00:20:44.092 --> 00:20:45.550 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Like a
stopping off point?

00:20:45.550 --> 00:20:46.350 align:middle line:90%
A stopping off.

00:20:46.350 --> 00:20:48.010 align:middle line:84%
Like if you had a
Tesla car, you'd

00:20:48.010 --> 00:20:49.350 align:middle line:90%
need to have a charging station.

00:20:49.350 --> 00:20:50.150 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:20:50.150 --> 00:20:53.930 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: So to open space, we
need to make fueling stations.

00:20:53.930 --> 00:20:56.870 align:middle line:84%
And that's a technique that
the group has come up with.

00:20:56.870 --> 00:20:58.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So British
astronaut, female,

00:20:58.790 --> 00:21:01.220 align:middle line:84%
one of the first for
the Brits, claims

00:21:01.220 --> 00:21:03.860 align:middle line:90%
that aliens are among us.

00:21:03.860 --> 00:21:05.720 align:middle line:84%
Now she's not
talking about people

00:21:05.720 --> 00:21:07.520 align:middle line:90%
who look like you and me.

00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:09.380 align:middle line:84%
But she's talking
about organisms

00:21:09.380 --> 00:21:11.330 align:middle line:90%
from other planets are here.

00:21:11.330 --> 00:21:12.950 align:middle line:90%
Do you accept that?

00:21:12.950 --> 00:21:16.020 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Well, we'd have
to get a sample of them

00:21:16.020 --> 00:21:18.770 align:middle line:84%
and sequence them to see
what their DNA looked

00:21:18.770 --> 00:21:20.750 align:middle line:84%
like because chances
are their DNA

00:21:20.750 --> 00:21:22.523 align:middle line:84%
wouldn't have the
same sequence as ours.

00:21:22.523 --> 00:21:24.440 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What about the
possibilities, though?

00:21:24.440 --> 00:21:25.370 align:middle line:90%
Is it?

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:26.550 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: It's possible.

00:21:26.550 --> 00:21:28.970 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes that's
called panspermia.

00:21:28.970 --> 00:21:31.370 align:middle line:84%
You may have covered
that in previous show.

00:21:31.370 --> 00:21:32.480 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Absolutely.

00:21:32.480 --> 00:21:34.520 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Here's the
challenge with panspermia.

00:21:34.520 --> 00:21:37.070 align:middle line:84%
So instead of this material
falling on the Earth

00:21:37.070 --> 00:21:40.250 align:middle line:84%
to feed a process like we did
in New Zealand, where we're

00:21:40.250 --> 00:21:43.130 align:middle line:84%
forming protocells,
what if life could

00:21:43.130 --> 00:21:46.670 align:middle line:84%
come from outside as a
complete cell that came in?

00:21:46.670 --> 00:21:49.910 align:middle line:84%
The challenge is if life was
already here, it might eat it.

00:21:49.910 --> 00:21:52.010 align:middle line:84%
That's what Charles
Darwin thought.

00:21:52.010 --> 00:21:54.650 align:middle line:84%
Or if the Earth was very
toxic and difficult,

00:21:54.650 --> 00:21:58.100 align:middle line:84%
it might just expire,
might not thrive at all.

00:21:58.100 --> 00:22:00.170 align:middle line:84%
So if something
landed on Mars today,

00:22:00.170 --> 00:22:02.240 align:middle line:90%
it would just be sterilized.

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:05.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I've always liked
space since I was a kid.

00:22:05.410 --> 00:22:09.700 align:middle line:84%
But why is it so important
for us, as humans,

00:22:09.700 --> 00:22:12.370 align:middle line:90%
to explore these other worlds?

00:22:12.370 --> 00:22:14.950 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: I think, George,
because it teaches us how

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:17.590 align:middle line:90%
to be better stewards of ours.

00:22:17.590 --> 00:22:21.310 align:middle line:84%
So if we see what happened to
Venus with a heating event that

00:22:21.310 --> 00:22:23.290 align:middle line:84%
created a greenhouse,
runaway greenhouse,

00:22:23.290 --> 00:22:25.930 align:middle line:84%
and basically
killed Venus, we can

00:22:25.930 --> 00:22:29.320 align:middle line:84%
learn about the dangers of
managing the amount of CO2

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:32.080 align:middle line:84%
in our atmosphere
because we look at Venus,

00:22:32.080 --> 00:22:34.930 align:middle line:84%
and that's like, that's
what happens to planets when

00:22:34.930 --> 00:22:36.290 align:middle line:90%
the CO2 is the atmosphere.

00:22:36.290 --> 00:22:38.090 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What can
we do about it?

00:22:38.090 --> 00:22:41.710 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Well, that's where
we came in with the US Navy.

00:22:41.710 --> 00:22:45.520 align:middle line:84%
So about 15 years ago,
as part of a study--

00:22:45.520 --> 00:22:46.547 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: With the Navy?

00:22:46.547 --> 00:22:48.880 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Well, this was for
the Office of Net Assessment

00:22:48.880 --> 00:22:52.070 align:middle line:84%
at the Pentagon, where
they were saying,

00:22:52.070 --> 00:22:56.120 align:middle line:84%
how can we get America off
dependence on foreign oil?

00:22:56.120 --> 00:23:00.310 align:middle line:84%
So we did a study with Andrew
Marshall and Peter Schwartz

00:23:00.310 --> 00:23:01.780 align:middle line:90%
for the Pentagon.

00:23:01.780 --> 00:23:05.530 align:middle line:84%
And that kicked off
a series of studies

00:23:05.530 --> 00:23:08.020 align:middle line:84%
from the highest level that
was commissioned by the Joint

00:23:08.020 --> 00:23:10.360 align:middle line:84%
Chiefs, and especially
in the Navy,

00:23:10.360 --> 00:23:14.560 align:middle line:84%
on global security tied to
climate change and climate

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:16.390 align:middle line:90%
shocks, they're called.

00:23:16.390 --> 00:23:20.230 align:middle line:84%
And so that's now activated
the Department of Defense.

00:23:20.230 --> 00:23:21.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, these
climate shocks,

00:23:21.730 --> 00:23:23.420 align:middle line:90%
what are they specifically?

00:23:23.420 --> 00:23:26.088 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: So for example, what's
happening in Australia right

00:23:26.088 --> 00:23:27.880 align:middle line:84%
now, where I'm headed
in a couple of weeks.

00:23:27.880 --> 00:23:29.020 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Well, be safe.

00:23:29.020 --> 00:23:32.050 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: Yeah, where the
whole place is on fire.

00:23:32.050 --> 00:23:34.450 align:middle line:84%
And climatologists
now believe that one

00:23:34.450 --> 00:23:36.400 align:middle line:84%
of the next targets
for wildfires

00:23:36.400 --> 00:23:39.160 align:middle line:90%
will be the American southeast.

00:23:39.160 --> 00:23:42.670 align:middle line:84%
And all you need to get
wildfires started is, say--

00:23:42.670 --> 00:23:44.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: A spark in
a dry area, right?

00:23:44.990 --> 00:23:45.790 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Right.

00:23:45.790 --> 00:23:47.530 align:middle line:84%
So say, if in South
Carolina, they

00:23:47.530 --> 00:23:51.670 align:middle line:84%
have a unusual dry
30-day period, that

00:23:51.670 --> 00:23:55.690 align:middle line:84%
is enough to dry out
the vegetation and all

00:23:55.690 --> 00:23:57.620 align:middle line:90%
that kudzu and everything.

00:23:57.620 --> 00:24:00.730 align:middle line:84%
And so you're going to see,
by the mid- to late '30s,

00:24:00.730 --> 00:24:03.730 align:middle line:84%
you're going to see wildfires
in places we've never seen them,

00:24:03.730 --> 00:24:07.510 align:middle line:84%
like in South Carolina,
like in Georgia, everywhere.

00:24:07.510 --> 00:24:09.940 align:middle line:84%
So then everybody's
under threat.

00:24:09.940 --> 00:24:12.970 align:middle line:10%
All those neighborhoods,
all those businesses.

00:24:12.970 --> 00:24:15.670 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Could some of these
be deliberately set as well?

00:24:15.670 --> 00:24:18.820 align:middle line:10%
>>DAMER: Well, they'll start
from all kinds of sources.

00:24:18.820 --> 00:24:21.640 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you just spark
the back of a pickup

00:24:21.640 --> 00:24:22.820 align:middle line:90%
and you can set a fire.

00:24:22.820 --> 00:24:25.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And how do you respond
to those climate shocks?

00:24:25.390 --> 00:24:27.430 align:middle line:90%
How do you solve that?

00:24:27.430 --> 00:24:29.470 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: So this is where
the Pentagon comes in.

00:24:29.470 --> 00:24:34.240 align:middle line:84%
So I met Admiral Norman Hayes
in Qatar in the Middle East

00:24:34.240 --> 00:24:35.650 align:middle line:90%
about a year ago.

00:24:35.650 --> 00:24:37.240 align:middle line:84%
We were walking
around and we noticed

00:24:37.240 --> 00:24:40.330 align:middle line:84%
that they had built half a
trillion dollars of skyscrapers

00:24:40.330 --> 00:24:42.363 align:middle line:84%
and World Cup
stadiums and whatnot.

00:24:42.363 --> 00:24:43.780 align:middle line:84%
And it was all
going to be rusting

00:24:43.780 --> 00:24:46.960 align:middle line:84%
scaffolding because they built
it at or under sea level.

00:24:46.960 --> 00:24:48.700 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Why would they do that?

00:24:48.700 --> 00:24:51.380 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: You know,
nobody thought about it.

00:24:51.380 --> 00:24:53.380 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How could they miss it?

00:24:53.380 --> 00:24:55.390 align:middle line:84%
That would be the
first question I'd ask.

00:24:55.390 --> 00:24:58.872 align:middle line:84%
Folks, you know, we're
building this on a sand barge.

00:24:58.872 --> 00:24:59.830 align:middle line:90%
What's going to happen?

00:24:59.830 --> 00:25:03.010 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: And Google and
Facebook completed $10 billion

00:25:03.010 --> 00:25:06.730 align:middle line:84%
on campus construction on the
Bay, on the San Francisco Bay,

00:25:06.730 --> 00:25:08.470 align:middle line:90%
and there's a panic now.

00:25:08.470 --> 00:25:13.312 align:middle line:84%
So they went to say is there
any plan for a Bay Area seawall

00:25:13.312 --> 00:25:15.020 align:middle line:84%
because we're going
to lose our campuses.

00:25:15.020 --> 00:25:17.710 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How tall does
this seawall have to be?

00:25:17.710 --> 00:25:18.980 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: It's a good question.

00:25:18.980 --> 00:25:22.870 align:middle line:84%
So SFO San Francisco Airport,
where you'll be flying in,

00:25:22.870 --> 00:25:25.300 align:middle line:84%
is going to be building a
seawall for their runway

00:25:25.300 --> 00:25:28.293 align:middle line:84%
because all the airports
are under threat worldwide.

00:25:28.293 --> 00:25:29.710 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: These
mood shocks, you've

00:25:29.710 --> 00:25:32.050 align:middle line:10%
identified really
10 specific goals

00:25:32.050 --> 00:25:33.520 align:middle line:10%
to respond to these shocks.

00:25:33.520 --> 00:25:35.228 align:middle line:10%
Can you go through a
few of those for us?

00:25:35.228 --> 00:25:36.028 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Yeah.

00:25:36.028 --> 00:25:37.600 align:middle line:84%
Some of them are
like the sea level.

00:25:37.600 --> 00:25:41.530 align:middle line:84%
We have to build 11,000
miles of sea level, sea rise

00:25:41.530 --> 00:25:43.620 align:middle line:90%
mitigation, infrastructure.

00:25:43.620 --> 00:25:44.740 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: 11,000 miles.

00:25:44.740 --> 00:25:50.500 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: 11,000 miles worldwide
just to preserve the high value

00:25:50.500 --> 00:25:51.880 align:middle line:90%
coastal cities.

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:54.283 align:middle line:84%
Cities like Jakarta
are going to disappear.

00:25:54.283 --> 00:25:55.450 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How about New York?

00:25:55.450 --> 00:25:56.650 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: New York, yeah.

00:25:56.650 --> 00:25:57.460 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: LA.

00:25:57.460 --> 00:26:00.700 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: Bangkok, Delhi.

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:01.848 align:middle line:90%
You just name them.

00:26:01.848 --> 00:26:03.140 align:middle line:90%
I mean, there are just so many.

00:26:03.140 --> 00:26:05.620 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How high will
the sea levels rise?

00:26:05.620 --> 00:26:07.210 align:middle line:90%
>>DAMER: No one knows for sure.

00:26:07.210 --> 00:26:09.100 align:middle line:84%
But here's the
challenge, George.

00:26:09.100 --> 00:26:11.380 align:middle line:84%
So Houston is a
city that is totally

00:26:11.380 --> 00:26:13.160 align:middle line:90%
activated at this point.

00:26:13.160 --> 00:26:16.060 align:middle line:84%
So if you go to Houston and
you go to the Natural History

00:26:16.060 --> 00:26:20.260 align:middle line:84%
Museum, there's a fantastic
projection map display

00:26:20.260 --> 00:26:23.900 align:middle line:84%
showing what Houston will look
like with a two-inch rise,

00:26:23.900 --> 00:26:25.978 align:middle line:84%
a four-inch rise,
a six-inch rise.

00:26:25.978 --> 00:26:27.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Which is
seems like nothing.

00:26:27.520 --> 00:26:29.187 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: It seems
like nothing, but what

00:26:29.187 --> 00:26:32.050 align:middle line:84%
it does, at the same time
as the Gulf is going up

00:26:32.050 --> 00:26:35.290 align:middle line:84%
two, four, six, eight inches,
the water is getting warmer.

00:26:35.290 --> 00:26:36.910 align:middle line:84%
The hurricanes
are more powerful.

00:26:36.910 --> 00:26:41.550 align:middle line:84%
The storm surges are bigger
by more than two inches,

00:26:41.550 --> 00:26:42.820 align:middle line:90%
by a magnifier.

00:26:42.820 --> 00:26:45.290 align:middle line:84%
And so they are
showing the devastation

00:26:45.290 --> 00:26:48.440 align:middle line:84%
that Houston will experience,
which highways will become

00:26:48.440 --> 00:26:51.430 align:middle line:90%
impassible with these things.

00:26:51.430 --> 00:26:53.980 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But would a
barrier really work, Bruce?

00:26:53.980 --> 00:26:56.140 align:middle line:84%
>>DAMER: It can, but
we have to rethink

00:26:56.140 --> 00:26:58.450 align:middle line:90%
how we do seawall barriers.

00:26:58.450 --> 00:27:01.660 align:middle line:84%
So when you're back on the
east coast, if you fly in,

00:27:01.660 --> 00:27:04.150 align:middle line:84%
you'll see all those
barrier islands.

00:27:04.150 --> 00:27:08.140 align:middle line:84%
That's nature's way of
creating a seawall for storms.

00:27:08.140 --> 00:27:10.190 align:middle line:84%
And that was just created
by piling up sand,

00:27:10.190 --> 00:27:11.500 align:middle line:90%
but they're living.

00:27:11.500 --> 00:27:13.900 align:middle line:84%
Things are growing on
them, so they self-repair.

00:27:13.900 --> 00:27:16.930 align:middle line:84%
Or so we can learn from nature
to build living seawalls

00:27:16.930 --> 00:27:18.490 align:middle line:90%
instead of concrete abutments.

00:27:18.490 --> 00:27:21.280 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What else do you need
to do in some of these things?

00:27:21.280 --> 00:27:24.010 align:middle line:84%
